{
  "terms": [
    {
      "term": "Ammeter",
      "simpleDefinition": "A device used to measure the flow of electric current in a circuit.",
      "anchor": "Think of it as a flow meter in a pipe, measuring how much electricity is passing through a point.",
      "misconception": "Often incorrectly called a 'current meter' or confused with a voltmeter."
    },
    {
      "term": "Voltmeter",
      "simpleDefinition": "An instrument used to measure the electrical potential difference (voltage) between two points.",
      "anchor": "Like a pressure gauge measuring the 'push' or force between two parts of a system.",
      "misconception": "Believing it measures the flow of electricity rather than the pressure difference."
    },
    {
      "term": "Ohmmeter",
      "simpleDefinition": "A device used to measure electrical resistance within a component or circuit.",
      "anchor": "Measures how much a material 'fights' or resists the flow of current.",
      "misconception": "Thinking resistance can be measured while the circuit is powered on."
    },
    {
      "term": "Wattmeter",
      "simpleDefinition": "An instrument used to measure the rate of power being used in a circuit at that exact moment.",
      "anchor": "Measures the 'work rate' of the electricity, similar to a speedometer showing current speed.",
      "misconception": "Confusing instantaneous power (Watts) with total energy used over time (kWh)."
    },
    {
      "term": "Energy Meter",
      "simpleDefinition": "A device that measures the total amount of electrical energy consumed over a period of time.",
      "anchor": "The 'billing meter' in a house that records total usage in kilowatt-hours (kWh).",
      "misconception": "Thinking an energy meter and a wattmeter perform the same function."
    },
    {
      "term": "Multimeter",
      "simpleDefinition": "A single handheld instrument that can perform multiple functions, typically acting as a voltmeter, ammeter, and ohmmeter.",
      "anchor": "The 'Swiss Army Knife' of electrical testing tools.",
      "misconception": "Assuming a standard multimeter can measure every quantity, such as power or energy, without specialized settings or attachments."
    }
  ],
  "anchorPhrases": [
    "Ammeters measure current flow.",
    "Voltmeters measure electrical pressure.",
    "Ohmmeters measure resistance.",
    "Wattmeters measure instantaneous power.",
    "Energy meters measure total consumption over time."
  ],
  "misconceptionTargets": [
    "Power and energy are the same thing and use the same meter.",
    "A multimeter is the only tool needed for all electrical measurements.",
    "Using imprecise terms like 'power meter' when you mean an ammeter or voltmeter."
  ]
}

[
  {
    "title": "Measuring Voltage, Current, and Resistance",
    "objective": "Identify the specific instruments used to measure voltage, current, and resistance.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "To work safely and accurately as an electrician, you must select the correct instrument for the specific quantity you are measuring. We start with the three core quantities: current, voltage, and resistance. To measure the flow of electricity through a circuit, you use an Ammeter. Think of this like a flow meter in a water pipe; it tracks how much electricity passes a specific point. To measure the electrical potential difference, or the 'pressure' between two points, you use a Voltmeter.",
      "If you need to find out how much a component resists that flow, you use an Ohmmeter. It is vital to remember that resistance is measured on unpowered circuits to prevent damage to the device. Most modern electricians use a Multimeter, which is a single handheld device that combines these functions. While it acts as a 'Swiss Army Knife' for testing, you must manually select the correct mode. Using an ammeter setting to measure voltage, for example, can cause a short circuit and destroy the instrument."
    ],
    "hint": "Think about whether you are measuring flow, pressure, or resistance, and remember that a multimeter can often do all three if set correctly."
  },
  {
    "title": "Measuring Power and Energy",
    "objective": "Distinguish between the instruments used for measuring instantaneous power and total energy consumption.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "While voltage and current are fundamental, we also need to measure the work being done by electricity. This is where power and energy come in. These two quantities are often confused, but they require distinct instruments. To measure the 'work rate' or the instantaneous power being used at a specific moment, you use a Wattmeter. This is similar to a speedometer in a car, showing you exactly what is happening right now in terms of load.",
      "In contrast, if you need to measure the total amount of electricity consumed over a period of time, you use an Energy Meter (often referred to as a kWh meter). This is the 'billing meter' found in domestic installations that records total usage for the electricity supplier. You must be technically precise: a Wattmeter measures the rate (Watts), while an Energy Meter measures the total consumption (kilowatt-hours). A standard multimeter usually cannot measure these quantities directly, so specific dedicated meters are required for these tasks."
    ],
    "hint": "One meter shows what is happening 'right now' (power), while the other acts like a counter for total usage over time (energy)."
  }
]

